WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standalone formula reference for video compression,
quality metrics, and timecode arithmetic.

WHY IT EXISTS
These equations are essential for codec evaluation, automated QC, and
frame‑accurate editing. Without a central reference, different tools
calculate VMAF or drop‑frame timecode differently.

HOW IT WORKS
Definitive formulas for VMAF, CCLM prediction, AV1 rate‑distortion
optimisation, and SMPTE drop‑frame timecode.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Encoding pipelines (AV1, VVC, AV2)
- Streaming quality monitoring (VMAF)
- Editorial and broadcast timecode systems

WHO USES IT
L2 Engineers writing codec plugins; QC technicians; broadcast engineers.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Standardises the computation of VMAF and timecode so that a GIOP‑certified
encoder and decoder produce identical quality scores and frame numbers.

1. VMAF (Video Multimethod Assessment Fusion)
   Elementary metrics per frame:
     VIF: Visual Information Fidelity (steerable pyramid)
     ADM: Additive Detail Metric (wavelet domain)
     Motion: temporal difference magnitude
   Feature vector F = [VIF, ADM, Motion]
   SVM fusion:
     VMAF = Σ w_i * K(F, support_vector_i) + b
   Trained on the Netflix public dataset (>10⁴ clips, >10⁵ human ratings).
   Pearson correlation with subjective MOS ≈ 0.98.
   GIOP uses the standard VMAF model version specified in the runtime
   configuration.

2. CCLM Prediction (H.266/VVC)
   Chroma block C predicted from down‑sampled luma L′:
     pred_C[i,j] = a * L′[i,j] + b
   where (a,b) are derived from neighbouring reconstructed samples via
   linear regression:
     a = (N * Σ(L′*C) - ΣL′ * ΣC) / (N * Σ(L′²) - (ΣL′)²)
     b = (ΣC - a * ΣL′) / N
   This reduces chroma residual energy by ~40% vs HEVC.

3. AV1 Rate‑Distortion Optimisation (Lagrange Multiplier)
   Mode decision:
     J = D + λ * R
   λ derived from quantisation parameter QP and temporal layer:
     λ = λ_base * Q_scale[QP][layer]
   For HDR, a luminance‑weighted distortion term biases λ toward
   preserving shadow detail.

4. SMPTE ST 12‑1 Drop‑Frame Timecode
   Frame rate: 30/1.001 ≈ 29.97002997 fps.
   Drop‑frame rule:
     dropped_frames = 2 * (minutes - floor(minutes/10))
     N_drop_frame = N_total - dropped_frames
   Time in seconds: T = N_drop_frame / 29.97002997

